humanMachineDialogue.text: The report states that a left axillary lymph node dissection was performed and metastatic breast carcinoma was identified in 14 of 18 nodes examined. This corresponds to N2, which indicates metastases in 4 to 9 axillary lymph nodes. The specific number of positive lymph nodes is not explicitly stated as 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, or 9, but it is clear that it falls within this range. Extranodal extension was also present, but this does not affect the N stage.

humanMachineDialogue.author: ZS Reasoning
humanMachineDialogue.text: The report indicates that a left axillary lymph node dissection was performed and metastatic breast carcinoma was identified in 14 out of 18 nodes examined. This corresponds to an N2 stage, as defined by the American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) staging system for breast cancer. The AJCC system classifies N1 as 1-3 positive nodes, N2 as 4-9 positive nodes, and N3 as 10 or more positive nodes. The presence of extranodal extension also supports the N2 classification.
